    ],
    "rationale": "This reaction shows the decarbonylation of a simple, long-chain aliphatic aldehyde (octanal) to the corresponding alkane (heptane) using Wilkinson's catalyst. This is a classic, textbook example of the Tsuji-Wilkinson decarbonylation, clearly illustrating the deformylation of an aldehyde to an alkane with the loss of carbon monoxide. The use of a simple, acyclic, saturated substrate avoids ambiguity with other named reactions.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a simple aliphatic aldehyde, avoiding aromatic rings (which could trigger Friedel-Crafts or other arene-related reactions), unsaturation near the carbonyl (avoiding conjugate addition/Michael-type reactions), or other functional groups. This specific transformation (R-CHO -> R-H) is highly characteristic of this named reaction and is unlikely to be confused with other common decarbonylation or decarboxylation reactions that typically start from carboxylic acids, esters, or acid chlorides."
  }
}
